<font color="#FF0000">HOW SHOULD VNW BE TREATED</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 13 22:39:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
  I have been a recruiter w/ the CA Army National Guard for the past 12 years &amp; spend time in our local High Schools; I have spent numerous hours in front of students discussing the VNam War &amp; it'll never cease to amaze me how many have a close relative that was involved &amp; how many know so little. I begin by laying one ground rule: Don't ask me if I killed anyone, because #1, that's not the focus of the class &amp; #2, I was in a war. (USMC 1st Bn/4th Marines, all of 1966). That seems to set the tone &amp; I'll continue by explaininmg that the War was different to each individual, depending on where they were both chronologically &amp; physically &amp; depending upon the job they did. I keep it upbeat w/ an open window for any plausible question (there are those who need to hear themselves making noises) &amp; it seems to work well. I've had many mixed reactions from being asked if I was a druggie (Ans: There were no drugs in the field in my units &amp; yes, I did struggle w/ alcohol after I came back) to a young lady that prefaced her comment w/ an apology if she sounded like she was giving a &quot;canned&quot; comment, but wanted to say, &quot;Welcome home &amp; thanks&quot;. That one sort of got to me. All in all, my experiences have been positive when the young people wanted to listen &amp; take part. <br>
   That's the positive that I have to add; the negatory is that there are very few curriculum that do more than a cursory mention of the VNam War. It's sad, as we continue to live it's legacy &amp; we owe our younger generations knowledge of our lessons learned; providing, of course, that they want to hear it.   <br>

